ayers alongside each other, Chaucer's Prayers cuts across an assumed division between the "religious" and "secular" writings within Chaucer's corpus. Rather, it emphasizes continuities andapproaches prayer as part of Chaucer's broader experimentation with literary voice. It also places Chaucer in his devotional context and foregrounds how pious practices intersect with and shape his poetic practices. These insightschallenge a received view of Chaucer as an essentially secular poet and shed new light on his poetry's relationship to religion. MEGAN MURTON is Assistant Professor of English at The Catholic University of America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrayers, Medieval. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChaucer's poetry.  aChaucer's prayers.  aChaucerian literature.  aChristian devotion.  aChristian literature.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary devotion.  aliterary practice.  aliterary voice.  amedieval Christianity.  amedieval poetry.  amedieval prayers.  apagan devotion.  areligious themes.  areligious writings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787449145?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787449145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787449145/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles